<DESCRIPT>  BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The Berryessa Citizens Advisory Council is hosting "A President's Birthday
Celebration" featuring a presentation on the area's history by San Jose
historian Clyde Arbuckle and Elizabeth Maxey DeMarco, a descendant of the
historic Berryessa family.;    The program is scheduled to run from 7:30 p.m.
to 10 p.m. Monday at the Berryessa School District office, 1376 Piedmont Road
in San Jose. Also on hand will be council President Bill Hughes, who will
present a history of the Berryessa-area group.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PRESIDENTS REMEMBERED WITH HISTORY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  In Brief  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Among the invited guests at the event's reception are state Sen. Dan
McCorquodale, D-San Jose, county Supervisor Ron Gonzales and San Jose Mayor
Susan Hammer.; GRANTS AVAILABLE: The Community Foundation of Santa Clara
County Neighborhood Grants Program, made possible by grants from county
private organizations, is inviting neighborhood groups, tenant and homeowner
associations and others to apply for grants.;    Grants of up to $5,000 will
be available to help finance a wide range of projects in areas including, but
not limited to, projects such as graffiti removal, crime prevention, economic
development, small scale park and office space development, housing, human
services and multi-cultural events and activities.;    The foundation is
presenting a "Pre-Application Workshop" for those interested in learning more
about the Neighborhood Grants Program from 9:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. Friday at
the Non-profit Development Center, 1762 Technology Drive, Suite 225, in San
Jose.;    To register, prospective applicants can call either the center at
(408) 452-8181 or the Community Foundation at (408) 241-2666.;    SENIOR DAY:
Senior Day Services of Catholic Charities will host an open house to introduce
its new director, Christine Sarch, and its new socialization program for
elderly people with chronic mental illness.;    Senior Day Services is a
mental health day treatment program for Santa Clara County residents, age 55
and older, who suffer from serious mental illness such as depression, anxiety,
manic depression or schizophrenia. The program is intended to help
participants live independently. Fees are based on ability to pay.;   
Services include assessment, individual or group therapy, a support group for
family members, a full range of programs to improve social and emotional
functions and transportation to and from the program.;    The open house will
be Feb. 12 from 4 p.m. to 6:30 p.m. at 1509 Warburton Ave., Santa Clara. For
information, call (408) 247-0534.;    REAL ESTATE EDUCATION: The San
Jose-Evergreen Community College District, in cooperation with the San Jose
Real Estate Board, is recruiting students for its spring semester Real Estate
Work Experience Program that started last Monday at the San Jose Real Estate
Board, 1451 Fruitdale Ave. in San Jose.;    The program allows students who
have completed the three-unit real estate principles course to earn one to
four semester units of credit from either San Jose City College or Evergreen
Valley College while working in a real estate office. Students may work as
interns for up to 10 hours a week for 18 weeks. Subject areas include
residential and commercial real estate, fair housing laws, computer skills,
legal issues and other related topics.;    For registration information, call
the Office of Admissions and Records at SJCC, (408) 288-3700, or the office at
EVC, (408) 270-6441.;    For information on the Real Estate Work Experience
Program, call the San Jose Real Estate Board's Education Department at (408)
998-7300, extension 250 or 251.;    PIANO COMPETITION: The finals of the 1991
Young Pianists Concerto Competition will take place at 2 p.m. Sunday at the
Center for the Performing Arts in San Jose. Eight pianists ages 19 through 29
will compete for a $5,000 cash award and a stint with the San Jose Symphony
during the 1991-'92 season. The finalists were selected from an international
field of more than 60 entrants via taped auditions.;    Judges for the
competition include Maestro George Cleve, San Jose Symphony music director,
and pianist Ivan Moravec from Czechoslovakia.;    The competition will be
presented in two parts, from 2 p.m. to 5 p.m. and 7 p.m. to 10 p.m., with a
dinner break. Tickets are $10 for general admission and $5 for students and
seniors.;    Ticket information is available through the San Jose Symphony Box
Office, (408) 288-2828 and through BASS/Ticketmaster.;    DISASTER AID: Public
agencies in Santa Clara County have until March 8 to apply for assistance for
damages suffered during the December-January winter freeze. City and County
government agencies, public utilities, community college districts and other
agencies and special districts are eligible for state aid under the Natural
Disaster Assistance Act.;    The funds can be used to pay for labor and
overtime costs, equipment, supplies and facility repairs and reconstruction.; 
  After freezing temperatures from Dec. 21 through Jan. 2, the county board of
supervisors declared a local emergency on Jan. 8 because of agricultural
losses and water system damages. Gov. Pete Wilson then proclaimed a state of
emergency in Santa Clara and 16 other California counties Jan. 11.;    Under
state law, public aid, agencies must submit disaster aid applications within
60 days of the local emergency declaration date.;    Questions concerning
requirements can be addressed to Charles Wynn, Disaster Assistance Division,
State of California Office of Emergency Services, 2800 Meadowview Road,
Sacramento, CA 95832. The agency's phone number is (916) 427-4347.  </TEXT>
